   :gist "the relay needs :drop; the action vocabulary is where that gap already lives."}
  {:from "hg" :into "scripts/pattern_authority_gate.clj"
   :gist "the gate exists and its controls are sound; it needs re-running on channel 1."}
  {:from "hm" :into "futon2/holes/N-patterns-as-arrows.md"
   :gist "the formalism that says what a cascade IS; DarkTower/Patterns/ is being formalised now."}]

 :cascade/holes
 [{:id "hole-vocab" :severity :blocking
   :gist "The action vocabulary is FOUR macro actions: [:hold :forage :return :pheromone] (policy.clj:12). No pattern can add one. Every inherited pattern only REWEIGHTS them; two of them (hp, pt) are pure penalties with no info-gain, so they can only restrict. `hc` (the relay) is the first pattern wanting a capability — and it cannot be written."}
  {:id "hole-compose" :severity :blocking
   :gist "`:pattern/active` is singular — one pattern at a time. A cascade is by definition composed. Composition is not merely unimplemented: :cascade/contentions shows it is currently INCOHERENT (info 0.5 vs 0.6). Composition needs a resolution rule, and 'last write wins' is not one."}
  {:id "hole-channel1" :severity :open
   :gist "The patterns' declared parameters (@aif-delta) have never been tested. The gate tested only the hard-coded EFE reimplementation. `(cyber/attach-config ant :cyber/cargo-return)` is the untried path."}
  {:id "hole-because" :severity :latent
   :gist "Every BECAUSE in the library is about GENERALISATION ('the same logic applies to graph walkers'), not about the ant. And every NEXT-STEPS is 'bind this to Futon5's uplift'. The patterns' agency channel points at PORTING, not at foraging. They were written to export the ant, not to improve it — which is a reason the gate found nothing, distinct from the channel-1 gap."}]

 :cascade/filled-holes
 [{:id "hole-rubric" :from "futon7a lab/pattern-cascade cascade.edn"
   :gist "futon7a declares: 'An external evaluation rubric a third party holds (T-inf): xeno-evaluation cannot be self-supplied.' THE ANTS FILL THIS HOLE. Yield is external, world-supplied, and not self-reported: the ants just like to eat. That is precisely why the ant domain is grounded where the tokamak's objective is 'unanchored' — the tokamak tried to supply its own rubric. And the propagator theory says WHY no system can: a self-evaluating cascade is a fixed point of its own evaluation map, a 1-cycle, and equivariant maps exist iff every cycle is EVEN. One is odd. hole-rubric is a THEOREM, and the ants escape it by having a world."}]

 :cascade/shape
 {:free ["b0"]
  :free-note "Exactly one box with no incoming wire — the same shape as futon7a's cascade (a1 alone) and as Figure 8 (free = {7}). One given."
  :unsat ["contention :efe/:lambda/:info"]
  :unsat-note "The irreducible tension. In the constraint reading of the propagator (F-what-the-propagator-actually-does.md): FREE = the givens, CHAIN = the derivation, UNSAT = the HOWEVER. A cascade with no unsat core is frozen; this one has exactly one, and it is real."
  :sinks ["hm"]
  :sinks-note "Only the apex. Unlike futon7a, where `a2` is an undeclared sink (a THEN no IF consumes — a mechanically-findable strategic hole)."}}
